+++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
+
+gridfix2scm.pl  Convert Apache grid ECOs into Synopsys Scheme format
+

USAGE: gridfix2scm.pl [ -h ] [ -m <layermap_file> ] <gridfix_file>
       -h     - show this help message and exit
       -m     - use this layer map file

**** IMPORTANT NOTES ****
1.   The default output file will be gridfix.scm
2.   This program will ignore the "ADD via" commands in the gridfix file.
     It will assume that Apollo/Astro will automatically drop vias
     where possible.
3.   The layer map file is optional but highly recommended.
     The format of the layer map file are just layer and number pairs:

     metal1 31
     metal2 32
     metal3 33
     metal4 34

     These layer names and numbers must correspond to the input files and
     Apollo/Astro technology files
4.   This script will issue one "axgCreateStraps" command for each
     "ADD wire" command in the gridfix file.  This may be inefficient in terms
     of scheme code but it is a more reliable way of translating the added wires
5.   The "DELETE wire" and "DELETE via" commands translate into select and delete
     commands in scheme.   Although the deletion process is done as selectively as
     Apollo/Astro will allow, it is still a good idea to double check
     what has been deleted b/c of the nature of the selection command, some unintentional
     things may be selected and deleted

+++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
+
+mkmv.pl  Create an animated GIF of a RedHawk DvD movie cature
+


Usage:
    perl mkmv.pl [options] arguments

    Options: -h, -help, -man, -d n, -l n, -b n, -e n, -s n where "n" is an
    integer value

    Arguments: -i movie_dir, -o output_gif

Options:
    -h  Prints a short synopsis.

    -help
        Prints a synopsis and a description of program options and
        arguments.

    -man
        Prints the entire man page.

    -d n
        Sets the frame delay time to n * 10 milliseconds. Use this option to
        set the time lapse between frames in the output gif. The default is
        10 which sets the frame delay to 100mS or 10 frames/second.

    -l n
        Specifies the number of times the animation will loop (repeat)
        before stopping. Specifying a loop count of 0 causes the animation
        to loop forever. The default is 1.

    -b n
        Specifies the beginning frame number to use in the animation. Use
        this option to skip unwanted frames at the beginning of the
        animation. The default value is 1 (the first frame in the sequence).

    -e n
        Specifies the ending frame number to use in the animation sequence.
        Use this option to skip unwanted frames at the end of the animation.
        By default, all frames will be included.

    -s n
        Specifies the number of frames to skip in the animation sequence.
        Use this option to specify the number of interleaved frames that
        will be omitted from the animation. If specified, the program will
        output the first frame specified (see -b option), skip the next n-1
        frames, output the next frame, skip the next n-1 frames, and so
        forth until all frames are processed. In other words, 1 of n frames
        are included in the final animation. The default value is 1 (output
        all frames).

Arguments:
    -i movie_dir
        The path to the directory where the DvD movie was stored. RedHawk
        will by default store the DvD movie in ".apache/.movie" but the user
        also has the option to specify a custom movie directory. Use this
        option to specify the same directory as that specified in the
        RedHawk GUI when the movie was generated. You may use realitive or
        absolute paths.

    -o output_gif
        The path to the output file for the animated gif. Once again, you
        may specify realitive or absolute paths.

